			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2023</a> paper:</span><br><i>Deriving Integrated Multi-Viewpoint Modeling Languages from Heterogeneous Modeling Languages: An Experience Report</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/MalteHeithoff.html">Malte Heithoff</a>, <a href="../profile/NicoJansen.html">Nico Jansen</a>, <a href="../profile/JörgChristianKirchhof.html">Jörg Christian Kirchhof</a>, <a href="../profile/JudithMichael.html">Judith Michael</a>, <a href="../profile/FlorianRademacher.html">Florian Rademacher</a>, <a href="../profile/BernhardRumpe.html">Bernhard Rumpe</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1145/3623476.3623527">10.1145/3623476.3623527</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t6a.html"><span class="tagM">T6A: Experience Reports</span></a><ul><li> The paper is explicitly an experience report on deriving integrated multi-viewpoint modelling languages in practice.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t1d.html"><span class="tagL">T1D: Composition</span></a><ul><li> The experience centers on integrating multiple heterogeneous viewpoints/languages into a cohesive modelling language.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3c.html"><span class="tagL">T3C: DSLs</span></a><ul><li> The subject matter is modelling languages used by domain experts, i.e., DSL engineering practice.
</li></ul></li></ul>
